      <hedline>
        <hl1>China and Darfur: Time for Pressure</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Darfur Collides With Olympics, and China Yields'' (Diplomatic Memo, front page, April 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Darfur Collides With Olympics, and China Yields'' (Diplomatic Memo, front page, April 13):</p>
        <p>So far China's tardy efforts to pressure the Sudanese government are solely cosmetic diplomacy. Added to the admirable initiatives of Mia Farrow, Steven Spielberg and Eric Reeves, a Darfur activist, should be a ''spectator boycott'' of the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing.</p>
        <p>Let the athletes converge on Beijing to compete and let the media cover the Games. But across the globe, sports fans should take a stand, ensure that the Beijing stadiums are empty and deprive the government of the hotel, restaurant, travel and tourist revenue it is counting on to recoup its costs.</p>
        <p>If by early 2008 the Chinese authorities realize that the revenue is lost and staging the Olympics will simply shame them, then perhaps the carnage in Darfur will be important enough for Beijing to put real pressure on Khartoum.</p>
        <p>David J. Scheffer  Chicago, April 13, 2007</p>
        <p>The writer, a former United States ambassador at large for war crimes issues, is director of the Center for International Human Rights, Northwestern University School of Law.</p>
      </block>
